# SESSION PROTOCOL

---

## ENTER SESSION CHECKLIST

Run this at the start of every new conversation before doing any work.

1. **Check the time**
   Run: `powershell -Command "Get-Date -Format 'dddd, MMMM dd yyyy h:mm tt'"`
   Report the time to Ryan and state peak vs. off-peak status.

2. **Pull latest from GitHub**
   Run: `cd "c:\App Development\sticker-quest"; git pull origin main`
   If there are conflicts or errors, report them to Ryan before proceeding.
   If already up to date, note it briefly and move on.

3. **Read PROJECT_CONTEXT.md**
   Confirm current phase, open flags, and any decisions that affect today's work.

4. **Read the last 2 entries in PATCH_NOTES.md**
   Know what was done in the last session and what was left unfinished.

5. **Give Ryan a 3-line briefing:**
   - "Current phase: [X]. Last session: [what was done]."
   - "Open items: [top 1-2 things that need to happen next]."
   - "Time status: [peak/off-peak and what that means today]."

6. **Ask what Ryan wants to work on** — do not assume and charge ahead.

---

## EXIT SESSION CHECKLIST

Run this before ending any conversation where meaningful work was done.

1. **Update PATCH_NOTES.md**
   Log what was accomplished, any decisions made, and any new open items.

2. **Update PROJECT_CONTEXT.md**
   If any decisions changed the project direction, phase status, or known flags — update it.

3. **Commit and push to GitHub**
   Run a git status to show Ryan what changed, then:
   - `git add .`
   - `git commit -m "Session summary: [brief description of what was done]"`
   - `git push origin main`
   Tell Ryan: "Everything is saved to GitHub. Your work is backed up."
   If push fails (auth issue, branch conflict), explain the problem in plain English
   and give Ryan a simple fix.

4. **Clear next move**
   End with the standard "Your next move:" line so Ryan always knows exactly
   what to do when he comes back.

5. **Flag anything time-sensitive**
   If something needs to happen before a deadline (e.g., March 27 Claude Pro sprint),
   say so explicitly at the end of the session.

---

## GITHUB PLAIN ENGLISH REFERENCE

- **Pull** = download the latest version from GitHub to your computer
- **Commit** = save a snapshot of your work with a description
- **Push** = upload your saved snapshots to GitHub
- **Branch** = a separate copy of the project to work on safely (not used yet)
- If Ryan is on a different computer, he pulls first to get the latest before working

---

## WHEN TO SKIP THE ENTRY BRIEFING

Skip the full briefing if:
- Ryan explicitly says "just answer this question" or "quick question"
- The conversation is clearly a single strategy question with no code work
- The session is a continuation within the same conversation thread

Still check the time if any Claude Pro recommendations will be made.
Still pull from GitHub at the start of any session involving code changes.
